Serum separator tubes contain an inert, thixotropic polymer polymer gel material with a spgr of approx. 1.04. Silica or glass particles that accelerate clotting may be associated with it. Aspiration of blood into the tube and subsequent centrifugation displaces the gel which settles like a disk between the cells and the plasma when the separation is done. RCF( relative centrifugal force) of at least $1,100 \times \mathrm{g}$ for gel release and barrier formation. The release of intracellular components into the serum is prevented by the barrier for several hours or some cases for several days.
Before venipunture the phlebotomist selects the appropriate tubes and needles (gauges 19-22) and they must be sterile and sharp.
-VENOUS OCCLUTION ----- It is rarely necessary to leave the tourniquet in place for more than 1 min . When the flow of blood in the large vein is obstructed by a tourniquet, the filtration pressure across the capillary wall is increased. This increase
causes fluids and compounds with molecular weight less than 5000 mwt to pass through the capillary wall. Slight changes might occur if left for 1 min but marked changes have been observed after 3 min . EG protein will increase by $4.9 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{l}$, ast(9.3), total choleterol(5.1), bili(8.4), iron(6.7) and potassium (< 6.2). The composition of blood drawn first will be the most representative of the circulating blood.
- Stress associated with blood collection can have affects in patients at any age. Cortisol and growth hormone concentration in plasma may increase. Particularly in young children who are frightened , struggling and held in physical restraint, collection may cause adrenal stimulation leading to an increase in plasma glucose concentration increase or increase in activities of enzymes that originate in the skeletal muscles.
- Vigorous sunction on a syringe during collection or forceful transfer from the syringe to the receiving vessel may cause haemolysis of blood.

\section*{(B) SKIN PUNCTURE}

This is done when only a small amount of blood is required. However this procedure is time consuming and the risk of infection is higher than that of venipunture since the finger tip is more difficult to sterilize than the anticubital fossa. . Care should be taken when prick to avoid reaching the bone. The depth should be less than
$\mathbf{2 . 5 ~ c m}$. . The finger should be held in such way that gravity assists the collection of blood on the finger tip . Massage of the finger to stimulate blood flow should be avoided. .For an infant less than 1 hear old , the lateral and medial plantar surface of the foot should be used for skin puncture. For the collection of blood on filter paper for neonatal screening, the skin is cleaned and punctured. Then the filter paper is gently touched against a very large drop of blood and allowed to soak and fill the marked area.

\section*{(C) ARTERIAL PUNCTURE}

This procedure requires considerable skills and it is usually performed by the clinician, or specially trained nurse technician. The preferred site puncture are:- radial artery at at the wrist, brachial artery in the elbow, and femoral artery in the groin.

\section*{ANTI COAGULANT AND PRESERVATIVES FOR BLOOD}
-If whole blood or plasma is required for analysis, an anticoagulant must be added to the specimen during collection time.
- Whole blood is rarely required for clinical chemistry tests, only for blood gases, lactate and glycosylated haemoglobin. Serum from coagulated blood is the choice for many analytes
- The use of plasma is usually required for emergency cases since the blood has to wait for $15-30 \mathrm{~min}$ for completion of coagulation before centrifugation.
- The other advantage is that plasma yield from a given volume of whole blood is always greater than the yield of serum.
- The only disadvantage is the formation of fibrous clots or fragments during plasma storage and subsequent risk of clogging the sample probe of autoanalyzer.
-HEPARIN-----is the most widely used anticoagulant for clinical chemical tests and causes least interferences . It acts by preventing the conversion of prothrombin to thrombin and thus the formation of fibrous fibrinogen. Types of heparin anticoagulant are ammonium and lithium heparin .
- ETHYLENEDIAMINE TETRA-ACETIC ACID (EDTA)---- This is a chelating agent and in concentration of $1-2 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{ml}$ of blood. It is used for haematological examination since it preserves cellular components of blood. It is used as disodium or dipotassium salt and the later is more soluble. It prevents coagulation by binding calcium , which is essential for the clotting process.. In clinical chemistry is used to collect blood for GLYCOSYLATED HAEMOGLOBIN (HBA1C) analysis.
- SODIUM FLUORIDE--- This is the best preservative of blood glucose, together with an anticoagulant such as potassium, sodium, ammonium or lithium oxalate, . It also acts as a weak anticoagulant. It exerts its preservative action by inhibiting the enzyme system involved in glycolysis. It is also an inhibitor of urease and many other enzymes. Glucose in blood specimen without antiglycolytic agent will decrease as much as $10 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{dl}(0.56 \mathrm{mmol} / \mathrm{l})$ per hour at $25{ }^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$. The decrease is even more in infants due to their increased metabolic activities of rbcs and in leukemia pts due to their high metabolic activity of the leucocytes. Sodium iodoacetate at a concentration of $2 \mathrm{mg} /$ ml of blood is an effective antiglycolytic agent and a substitute for sodium fluoride . It has no effect on urease and can be used when urea and glucose are requested in the same specimen.. It inhibits only creatine kinase and has no significant effect on the other parameters.

\section*{HAEMOLYSIS}

This is the breakdown of rbcs. Serum or plasma shows haemolysis when the [hb] exceeds $20 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{dl}$. Slight haemolysis has little effect on most of the values. Severe haemolysis causes a slight dilutional effect on the constituent present at a lower concentration in the rbcs than in the plasma. However a marked effect may be obtained on those constituents that are present at a higher concentration in the erythrocytes than in the plasma. Eg potassium, alp, ldh, mg, aldolase and INpo4 . IF an electrophoresis is done on an heamolized specimen, an additional band due to hb appears $=$ fibrinogen band..

\section*{CAUSES OF HAEMOLYSIS}
- use of wet blood containers.
- Excess preservative
- Pushing through the neddle when transferring it from the syringes into blood container.
- Spending a lot of time during bleeding..
- Shaking the blood container vigorously.
- Separating the blood immediately after bleeding..

\section*{URINE COLLECTION}
-The type of urine specimen to be collected is dictated by the tests to be performed.
- Generally urine for quantitative analysis must be collected over an interval of time eg 1,4 , or 24 hours.
- Untimed or random urine specimen are suitable for only very few biochemical tests. A clean, early morning specimen is generally the most concentrated and this is prepared for routine examination.eg testing for unusual compounds such as beta chorionic gonadotropin.
- A clean timed urine specimen is the one obtained at specific times of the day or during certain phases of micturition. A double voided specimen is the urine excreted during a timed period following a complete emptying of the bladder . It is used to assess glucose excretion during a glucose tolerance test procedure. Its collection must be timed in relation to the ingestion of glucose.
- When specimen must be collected over a specified period of time, the patient must adhere closely to the instructions with regard to diet or medication , to avoid interference of ingested compounds with analytical procedures.
- Appropriate information regarding the collection including warnings with respect to handling of the specimen, should appear on the bottle label.
- Urine cannot be collected at the same time for two or more tests for which different procedures are required.
- The removal of aliquots is not permissible even when the volume removed is measured and corrected for , since the excretion rate of most compounds varies throughout the day and the effect of the removal of some specimen on the total concentration cannot be corrected.

\section*{URINE PRESERVATIVES}
-Preservatives of urine specimens have different roles but are usually added to:-
- (i) reduce bacterial action or chemical decomposition.
- (ii) solubilize constituents that might otherwise precipitate out of solution.
