\section*{RENAL FUNCTION , DISODERS AND LABORATORY ANALYSIS}

\section*{(A) THE KIDNEY}
-A normal human being has two pair of kidneys which are located just below the level of the ribs at the back of the body,(retroperitoneal space) one on either side of the spine where they are protected from damage by the rib cage.
- Each kidney weigh (adult kidney) about 150 g and measures approximately 12 cms in length. And it is bean shaped.
- The major structural parts of the kidney include-:
a) Renal artery---this is the blood vessel that brings the cardiac output to the kidney.
b) Renal vein---this is the blood vessel that carries the blood from the kidney to the heart.
c) Central hilus---- this is the location where the renal artery. Renal vein and the ureters enter the kidney.
d) Renal pelvis--- this is the location where all the collecting ducts drain to form the ureter.
e) Calyses--- this is the converging point of the renal pyramaid (made of the collecting ducts). All the calyses join to form the renal pelvis.
f) Medulla--- This is a major point of the kidney which consist of the loop of henle and the collecting ducts.
g) Cortex----This is composed mainly of the glomeruli, proximal and distal tubules

\section*{B) THE FUNCTIONS OF THE KIDNEY}
-The functions of the kidney may be characterized as EXCRETORY, REGULATORY and ENDOCRINE.

\section*{1) EXCRETORY FUNCTION}
-Serves to rid the body of most of the undesirable end products of metabolism as well as any excess of inorganic substances ingested in the diet. The metabolic waste products include the non-protein nitrogenous compounds (NPN) eg urea, creatinine, and uric acid, a number of other organic acids including amino acids are excreted in small quantities.
- Diet contains a variable and usually excessive supply of sodium, potassium, chloride, calcium, phosphate, magnesium, sulphate and bicarbonates. The dramatic efficiency of the excretory function is illustrated by sodium ie body sodium content is maintained essentially constant regardless of whether daily sodium intake is 1 or 150 mmol or more.
- In order to achieve the excretion of the waste metabolic products and the ingested surpluses without disrupting homoestasis (this is the maintenance of the optimal chemical composition of the intra- and extra-cellular fluids through out the body), the kidney must exercise both its excretory and regulatory function.

\section*{2) REGULATORY FUNCTION}
- The regulatory function of the kidney plays a major role in homoestasis (this is the maintenance of the optimal chemical composition of the intra- and extra-cellular fluids through out the body). The mechanism of differential re-absorption and secretion located in the tubules of the nephron are effectors of regulation.(NB will be discussed in details in the formation of urine.\}

\section*{3) ENDOCRINE FUNCTION}
- The endocrine function of the kidney can be regarded as either primary or secondary. Primary because the kidney is an endocrine organ producing hormones eg Renin, Prostagladins and Erythropoeitin.

\section*{A) RENIN}
-Is a proteolytic enzyme synthesized and stored in juxtaglomerular cells located along the afferent arteries of the renal glomeruli. The primary stimuli for rennin release are a decrease in perfusion pressure to the juxtaglomerular apparatus and negative sodium balance. Following stimulation,rennin is released in the blood where it hydrolysis its substrate called angiotensinogen (this is a globulin synthesized in the liver) to produce angiotensin I, which is then rapidly converted to angiotensin ii by the circulating angiotensin- converting enzymes that is abundant in the lung. Angiotensin ii (which is a potent vasoconstrictor) stimulates the cells of the zone glomerulosa to produce aldosterone hormone. The rennin - angiotensin system is an important regulator of blood pressure, it is also responsive to sodium and potassium concentration and regulates the aldosterone effect on sodium-potassium exchange in the distal tubule

\section*{B) PROSTAGLANDINS-}
-These are a series of carbon 20 (C20) unsaturated fatty acids containing a cyclopentane ring. The parent fatty acid is prostanoic acid.
- Prostaglandins appear hormone like in action and are synthesized at the site of action in almost all tissues eg kidney, lung, spleen, gastrointestinal tract (GIT), thyroid, skin and brain.
- Prostaglandins are thought to play a great role in reproduction, blood pressure control and to act as mediators of inflammation. They have been reported to have many pharmacologic actions and have been used therapeutically to induce abortion via uterine smooth muscle contraction. In the kidney they have an effect on sodium concentration and increased free water clearance.

\section*{C) ERYTHROPOETIN}
-This is a glycoprotein hormone in nature produced by the kidney and acts on the bone marrow to stimulate the proliferation and maturation of erythrocytes precursors. Therefore anaemia is a prominent feature in of renal insufficiency.
In the secondary but no less important aspect of kidneys endocrine function, it is a site of degradation of insulin, glucagons and aldosterone. It is also an important location of the hydroxylation of 25-(OH)2D3 that produces 1,25$(\mathrm{OH}) 2 \mathrm{D} 3$,the most active known form of vitamin $\mathrm{D} . \mathrm{nb} /$ progressive , chronic renal failure is regularly associated with a combination of osteomalacia ( inadequate mineralization of bone), due to altered vitamin D metabolism, and osteitis fibrosa cystica, caused by secondary elevation of PTH levels.

\section*{THE NEPHRON}
-This is the functional unit of the kidney. Each kidney has approximately $\mathbf{1}$ million nephrons. The nephron consists structurally of $-: 1$ ) the glomerulus ( which is a spherical epitherial space invaginated by a capillary network that connects the afferent and efferent arterioles and 2) a tubule of epithelial cells continuous with the glomerular epithelial space and ultimately leading to collecting ducts that empty into the renal pelvis
- Three distinct processes take place in each nephron:-
1) The blood flowing through the capillaries of the glomerulus is filtered , the filtrate passing into the tubules through the glomerular membrane =this process is called GLOMERULAR FILTRATION. The glomerular filtrate contains most of the constituents of the blood with the exception of the protein which does not pass through the normal glomerular membrane in any appreciable quantity.
2) As the glomerular filtrate passes through the walls of the tubule, more solutes are added by secretion through the walls of the tubules from the adjoining blood vessels= This process is called TUBULAR SECRETION.
3) Solutes and water pass back into the blood from the tubules through the walls of the tubules $=$ This process is called TUBULAR REABSORPTION

The end product of these three processes passes through larger collecting tubules into the ureters which carry it into the bladder , from where it is excreted through the urethra as urine. The constituent of urine are the products of glomerular filtration plus the products of tubular secretion minus constituents returned into the blood through tubular reaabsorption.

