FORMATION OF URINE
-The FORMATION OF THE KIDNEY IS THE KEY ROLE OF THE KIDNEY. The urine formed by the kidney constitutes most of the undesirable end products of metabolism as well as any excess of inorganic substances ingested in the diet.
-The undesirable waste products of metabolism includes non-protein nitrogenous compounds such as urea, creatinine,uric acid . A number of organic acids including amino acids are excreted in small quantities. Excess inorganic substances excreted by the kidney includes sodium, potassium, chloride, calcium, phosphates, magnesium, sulphates and bicarbonates.
- In the formation of urine there are several activities involved which includes:
1) Filtration
2) Re-absorption and secretion (tubular function)
3) Hormonal function
1) FILTRATION PROCESS
-The first step in urine formation is filtration at the glomerulus of plasma water driven by a net filtration pressure of about 15 mmhg .
-The filtrate is referred to as ULTRAFILTRATE because its composition is essentially the same as that of that plasma, with notable absence of molecules of mwt above approximately 15,000 daltons.
- Each kidney contains about 1 million nephrons and about 170-200 litres of ultraflitrate pass through the glomeruli in 24 hours.nb/ In the passage of the glomeruli filtrate through the tubules, re-absorption of solutes and water in various regions of the tubules reduces the total volume to 0.4-2 litres per day.
- The filtration of blood at the bowmans capsule is a passive process, whereby the flow of fluid from the blood depends on the fact that hydrostatic pressure in the capillaries is greater than that in the tubules lumen.
- Any factor that reduces the pressure gradient will lower the filtration rate. An imbalance in the hydrostatic pressure $2^{0}$ to vascular collapse, renal arterial occlusive disease, inflammatory disease, or obstruction of urinary flow system results in a marked decrease in glomeruli filtration resulting with the formation of scanty urine (oliguria) or no formation of urine at all (anuria). The maintenance of glomeruli filtration is dependent on an adequate renal blood flow rate as well as adequate perfusion pressure. The normal renal blood supply is well designed to meet these needs.
2) RE-ABSORPTION AND SECRETION (TUBULAR FUNCTION)
- In the tubules the solute composition of the ultrafiltrate is altered by the processes of reabsorption and secretion so that the urine excreted may have a completely different composition from that of the original filtered fluid.
- Different regions of the tubule have been shown to specialize in certain functions.
a) In the proximal tubules , $60-80 \%$ of the ultrafiltrate is reabsorbed. This activity is a passive process.
b) Threshold substance ie glucose is also reabsorbed in the proximal tubule. $\mathrm{nb} /$ THRESHOLD SUBSTANCE-----Certain substances almost completely reabsorbed by the tubules when their [ ] in the plasma are relatively low , appear in the urine when their plasma levels are above a certain set point or threshold level.
- High threshold substances such as glucose and amino acids are almost completely reabsorbed by means of specific transport systems in the tubular cells.
- The appearance of high threshold substance in urine is evidence that the filtered load of the substance is exceeding the maximal reabsorption rate of its tubular cell transport system..
- The renal threshold of a filtered compound is therefore that plasma [ ] of the substance at which the tubular reabsorption rate is not sufficiently fast to remove all of the substance from the plasma ultrafiltrate , so that the substance spills over into the urine.
c) In the loop of henle, chloride and more sodium without water are reabsorbed, generating a dilute urine.
d) Water reabsorption in more distal tubules and collecting duct is then regulated by the antidiuretic hormone (ADH) . In the distal tubules, secretion is the prominent activity. It is in this region that hydrogen ions are secreted in exchange with the reabsorption of sodium ions. Bicarbonates are reclaimed from the urine in aid of acid-base regulation.-In the loop of henle and collecting duct there two mechanisms which are responsible for the nature of urine produced.. These are COUNTER CURRENT MULTIPLICATION and COUNTER CURRENT EXCHANGE..

\section*{**COUNTER CURRENT MULTIPLICATION}
-This is an active process
- It is responsible for the removal of solutes and reabsorption of water from the loop of henle and collecting duct
- This process occurs in the absence of ADH.
- It creates a urine low osmolality (diluted urine).
**COUNTER CURRENT EXCHANGE..
- This is a passive process.
- It is responsible for differential reabsorption of water without solutes from the loop of henle and collecting duct
- This process occurs in the presence of ADH.
- It creates a urine high osmolality (concentrated urine)

\section*{ANTI DIURETIC HORMONE MODE OF ACTION}
-ADH determines the [ ] of urine produced.
- It is produced in the hypothalamus and stored in the posterior pituitary
- The amount of ADH produced depends on the osmoreceptors present in the hypothalamus which are stimulated by the high plasma osmolality or low plasma volume (hypovolumea).
- ADH causes the pores in the collecting duct to increase in diameter permitting an increase amount of water to be osmoticaly reabsorbed into the renal medulla. The resulting urine osmolality becomes x 5 that of the plasma. - In the absence of ADH, eg in diabetic inspidus or a non response of the collecting tubules to ADH, large volumes of dilute urine results.-
However, at the distal collecting ducts ADH, not only increases the permeability of the cells to water but also to urea. . This is the main reason fro the rise in urinary osmolality.

\section*{RENAL DISORDERS}

INTRODUCTION- There are several renal disorders which are classified according to the clinical presentation and the kidney (nephron) structural change. Consequently, many names for renal diseases actually represent clinical syndromes and their structural basis as revealed by a renal biobsy.
- An additional difficulty in classifying renal diseases is the tendency of distinct primary disease to emerge with time into a single clinical entity, regardless of their initial etiology or anatomic region of injury. This is contributed by the fact that there is a great relationship between the anatomy and function of renal structures and their blood supply. For example any decrease in the normal cardiac output may impair all the functions of the nephron and produce the clinical syndrome of pre-renal azotomia (increased blood urea).If the decrease in the cardiac output is very severe it may lead to injury of the renal tubules and the syndrome of acute renal failure . The injury of the renal tubules triggers the release of renin from the kidney resulting with hypertension. Hypertension is in fact a
complication of many renal diseases of varied causes. Additionally severe hypertension itself can damage renal arterioles, further compromising nephron function.
- Irrespective of the initial cause of the injury whether immunological, injury of the glomerulus or toxic injury to the tubular cells, the ultimate result is the loss of complete nephron.
- Most of the renal disorders will start to be noticed when the nephrons have lost $75 \%$ of their functioning capacity. The loss of $>90 \%$ of the nephrons function resulting to end stage renal disease produces remarkably consistent clinical and laboratory picture. Once the renal disease has reached this stage, it may be impossible to determine the site and nature of the initial injury.
-Some of the renal disorders to be discussed includes: end stage renal failure/disease (ESRD), acute renal failure (ARF), chronic renal failure (CRF), glomerular diseases (GD) (for example-acute glomerulonephritis (GN) and nephrotic syndrome (NS))

\section*{END STAGE RENAL FAILURE (ESRF/ESRD)}
-This is the stage where the kidney has lost entirely (>90\%) its noble functions that is has failed to maintain adequate excretory, regulatory and endocrine function.
- This stage is characterized by the constellation of symptoms, physical signs and abnormal diagnostic studies. These characters can also be referred to as uremic syndrome. The classic signs of uremia includes:- progressive weakness and easy fatigability, hypertension, loss of appetite, nausea and vomiting, muscle wasting, tremors, abnormal mental function, frequent but shallow respiration and metabolic acidosis.. This syndrome progress to produce stupor, coma, and ultimately death unless support is provided by haemodialysis or successive renal transplantation..

\section*{ACUTE RENAL FAILURE (ARF)}
-This clinical syndrome occurs when there has been a rapid and severe reduction of GFR OF $<10 \mathrm{ML} / \mathrm{MIN}$.
- Patients with ARF are oliguric (reduced urine output) for example will produce $<400 \mathrm{mls}$ of urine after fluid challage.
-During this oliguric state the patient is unable to excrete water and sodium, leading to expansion of ECF which results to oedema, hypertension and congestive heart failure.
- Another feature of ARF is that water is retained in excess of salt producing hyponatreamia (low levels of sodium in the blood). If this hyponatreamia is very severe, central nervous system symptoms results ( for example: seizures and coma).
- Another feature encountered in ARF is inability of the nephron to excreate potassium resulting with life threatening hyperkaleamia (high levels of potassium in the blood).
- Other features seen in ARF are: retention of phosphate leading to hyperphosphotaemia and hypocalcaemia (inadequate mineralization).
- Accumulation of urea and creatinine is evident. When ARF is due to under perfusion (lesser blood supply to the kidney) of the kidney, BUN will accumulate in excess of creatinine ( high bun/creat ratio). The rise in serum creatinine and less often the increase in BUN is used to monitor the degree of renal impairment.
- Patients with ARF develop all symptoms of uremic syndrome. However anaemia and metabolic bone disease seen in CRF are not very prominent.
- Patients with ARF are at risk of getting gastrointestinal haemorrhage and systemic infection which are the major cause of death.
- Some causes of ARF includes:- crush (accident) syndrome, toxic injury to the kidney ( drug toxicity), hypertension and malaria.
- ARF is manageable by the control of the primary cause for example loss of blood (give blood transfusion), drug toxicity( withdrawal of the drug or giving an anti dose), hypertension ( control with hypertensive drugs).
- Recovery from ARF can be achieved by subjecting the patient to haemodialysis.

\section*{LABORATORY INVESTIGATIONS}
-serial monitoring of creatinine, GFR,(creatinine clearance), serum eletrolytes, urine volume, urinalysis and serum and urine osmolality.

\section*{CHRONIC RENAL FAILURE (CRF)}
-Pts who do not recover from ARF may develop CRF if early death does not occur.- CRF is the end result of a variety of many conditions such as: chronic glomerulonephritis, chronic obstructive uropathy, polycystic kidney disease, renal artery blockage and any other condition that causes tubular dysfucntion.
- As ARF progresses without any kind of treatment, more nephrons get damaged and the oliguric nature of the patient changes into anuric nature (total suppression of urine output) due to the fact that all the nephrons have been damaged resulting to no more urine output. The patient is said to be in a total renal shutdown.
-All the symptoms of uremia syndrome are very prominent in patients having CRF.
- Inability to excrete potassium resulting with hyperkalaemia is very evident as in the case of ARF. Hypernatreamia, hperphosphotaemia and hypocalcaemia are also evident.
- If not managed , this condition is often terminal with exceedingly high rise in urea, creatinine, potassium and marked severe acidosis.
- The life of CRF pt can be sustained by haemodialysis or a successive kidney transplant.

\section*{LABORATORY INVESTIGATIONS}
-serial monitoring of creatinine, GFR,(creatinine clearance), serum eletrolytes, uric acid, urine volume, urinalysis and serum and urine osmolality.

\section*{GLOMERULAR DISEASES}
-These are pathological factors that cause direct injury to the renal glomerulus while preserving tubular functions and may resemble pre-renal factors.
- Eventually, chronic progressive glomerular disease will affect blood supply to the tubules and this will result in the loss of complete nephrons producing CRF and the uremic syndrome.
- The two most common glomerular diseases are : acute glomerulonephritis and the nephritic syndrome.

\section*{ACUTE GLOMERULONEPHRITIS}
-This pathological process is related to recent group A beta - haemolytic streptococcal infection. Other causes includes :- reactions to drugs, acute infection of the kidney, systemic disease with immune complexes deposition in the kidney such as systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), bacterial endocarditis and recent viral infection.
- This condition is characterized by the rapid onset of haematuria, proteinuria, reduced GFR, sodium and water retention resulting to oedema, hypertension and congestive heart failure. Oliguria may also be evident.
- In pts suspected of acute post streptococcal glomerulonephritis, evidence of recent infection may be found in increased titres of antibodies to streptococcal extracellular products ie Antistreptolysin O (ASO).

\section*{NEPHROTIC SYNDROME}
- This pathological process is related any interference with the normal glomerular filtration processes.
- The glomelular capillary wall is a special membrane which is uniquely designed to support rapid utrafiltration and to retain nearly all proteins with in the plasma..
- The glomerulus capillary wall is composed of three structural elements:-
(i) a layer of endothelial ells
(ii) the glomerular basement membrane that separate the endothelial cells from epithelial cells.
(iii) The outer epithelial cell layer that is attached to the basement membrane by the discrete cytoplasmic extentions.

