\section*{RENAL CALCULI}

Renal calculi are usually composed of products of metabolism present in normal glomerular filtrate often at concentration near their maximum solubility. Minor changes in urinary composition may cause precipitation of such constituents in the kidney or in the urinary tract.

\section*{CONDITION FAVOURING CALCULI FORMATION}
(1) A high urinary concentration of one or more constituents of the glomerular filtration due to :-
(a) low urine volume with normal renal function due to restricted fluid intake or excessive fluid loss over a long period of time.
(b) a high rate of excretion of the metabolic product forming stone, due to high plasma levels than the filtrate levels or impairment of tubular re-absorption from the filtrate.
(c) change in ph of the urine often due to bacterial infection which favours precipitation of different salts at different hydrogen ion concentration (ph).
(d) urinary stagnation due to obstruction to urinary flow .
(e) lack of normal inhibitors:- eg pyrophosphate and glycoprotein which prevents the formation of calcium phosphate and calcium oxalate crystals respectively.
- Renal calculi (urinary calculi) constitute the following:-
(a) calcium containing salts----between $70-80 \%$ of all renal stones contain calcium.

Precipitation is favoured by hypercalciuria. Alkaline conditions favouring calcium phosphate precipitation and stone formation are usually present in pts with CRF due to urease spliting organisms such as proteus valgaris. These stones are usually hard, white and radiopaque.They are also small in size and are usually lodged in the ureters.
The management of these stones involves;-
** treatment of the primary cause eg urinary infection
** treatment of hypercalcaemia (by reducing dietary intake).
** maintain a high fluid intake both day and night
** use of thiazide diuretics to reduce urinary calcium excretion.
(b) Uric acid stones------This constitutes $10 \%$ of all renal stones. They are associated with hyperuricaemia with or without clinical gout. Precipitation is favoured by acidic urine. The stones are usually small, yellowish brown.
The management of these stones involves:-
** treatment of hyperuricaemia by reducing purine intake.
** increase renal excretion of urates by taking uricosuric drugs(probenecid and salicylates)
** a lot of fluid intake is encouraged both day and night.
(C) Cystine--- these stones are very rare and when present they resemble uric acid stones.
(d) xanthine stones - these are very uncommon and when present may be due to rare inborn error called xanthinuria. They have been reported during treatment with xanthine oxidase inhibitors. Such as allopurinol, which impair the conversion of xanthine to uric acid.

