(1) DIALYSIS
-Dialysis helps to remove urea and other toxic substances from plasma and collects electrolytes balance by dialyzing the patient's blood against fluid containing no urea and appropriate concentration of electrolytes, free ionized calcium and other plasma constituents.
-The principle forms of dialysis includes:-

\section*{(a)HAEMODIALYSIS}
- In haemodialysis, blood is passed through an artificial kidney(DIALYZER) . This dialyzer contains a fliud (dialyzing fluid or dialysate) which consists mainly of water . The water that make this dialysate is highly purified . The dialysate does not contain any of the substances intended to be cleared from the blood eg urea and creatinine. It
does contain some of the substances the body needs such as calcium and biocarbonates. The following are the function of the dialysis machine:-
(a) it pumps blood from the patient via the patients access (which can be either catheter (blood lines),fistula(an artery joined to a vein) or a graft (placed between an artery and a vein)., around the machine and back to the patient.
(b)it mixes and warms the dialysate which passes through the artificial kidney.
(c) it monitors what is in the dialysate to make sure the right amount of the right substance s are there throughout the dialysis session.
(d) it checks the blood for air so that none gets into the patients bloodstream. (prevents air embolism)
(e) it monitors the pressure of the patients blood in the access .
- NOTE / during dialysis , heparin is added into the blood circulating in the dialyzer to be prevent any formation of clots.
-The number of sessions and the dialyis period depends on :
(a) the amount of waste in the blood (urea and creatinine levels)
(b) the body size of the patient

\section*{(b) HAEMODIAFILTRATION}
-This is an improved form of haemodialysis where large volumes of water and solutes can be removed through a highly permeable membrane.

\section*{(c) CONTINOUS AMBULATORY PERITONEAL DIALYSIS (CAPD)}
- The folds of peritoneum are used as the dialyzing membranewith capillaries on one side and appropriate fluid of high osmolality infused into the peritoneum on the other side.
