\section*{BLOOD UREA NITROGEN(BUN)}

Urea is the major nitrogen containing metabolic product of protein metabolism in human.
Over $90 \%$ of urea excretion is through the kidney and $10 \%$ is through the skin and gastrointestinal tract.. Urea is filtered freely by the glomerulus. In the normal kidney $40-70 \%$ of the highly diffusible urea moves passively out of the renal tubules and enters the interstitium ultimately to re-enter plasma. The back diffusion of urea is dependent on the urine flow rate, and more enters the interstitium in a slow-flow state
-A wide variety of renal diseases can cause an increase in plasma urea concentration. Unfortunately , the usefulness of urea as an independent indicator of renal function is limited by the variability of its blood levels as a result of non renal factors. Mild dehydration, high protein diet , increased protein catabolism, muscle wasting as in starvation, reabsorption of blood proteins after a gastrointestinal haemorrage , treatment with cortisal or its synthetic analogs.
-The principal clinical utility of of plasma urea determination lies in its measurement conjunction with plasma creatinine.. Clinicians calculate a convenient relationship ie BUN/CREAT ratio. Normal individual on a normal diet has a ratio of 12-20. Lower values indicate acute tubular necrosis, low protein intake starvation or severe liver disease. High ratio may be seen in case of catabolic states of tissue breakdown, prerenal azotomia, high protein intake or after G.I HAEMORRAGE.. Thus the bun/creatinine can show great variability and is only a rough guide to the nature of the underlying abnormality.

