\section*{FLUID AND ELECTROLYTE MOVEMENT}

There are four ways in which fluid and electrolytes move in the body:-osmosis,diffusion, active transport and filtration.

\section*{(1) OSMOSIS}

\footnotetext{
*This is the movement of a solvent across a selectively permeable cell membrane from an area of higher concentration of solutes to an area of lower concentration of solutes until equilibrium is established. Water is the primary solvent that holds solutes (substances) in solution in the body. The concentration of these solutes in the body fluids is osmolality, whichis determined by the total solute concentrationwithin a a fluid compartment. Osmolality is measured as parts of solute per kilogram of water and is reported as milliosmols per $\mathrm{lkg}(\mathrm{mOsmol} / \mathrm{L})$. The osmolality of plasma is $275-295 \mathrm{mOsmol} / \mathrm{L}$. The greatest determinant of osmolality within a fluid compartment is sodium concentration.
}
*Tonicity---may be used to refer to the osmolality of a solution. Isotonic solutions have the same osmolality as body fluidseg $0.9 \%$ normal saline. With isotonic solutions, water remains in the intravascular compartment without any net flow across selective membranes
* hypertonic solutios-have a higher osmolality than body fluids eg $3 \%$ saline solution. With a hypertonic solution in the intravascular compartment, water moves out of the intracellular compartment(inside the cell) and into intravascular compartment that is hypertonic causing the cell to shrink
*hypotonic solutions have a lower osmolality than the body fluids eg $0.45 \%$ saline. With hypotonic solutions water moves out of the intravascular compartment into intracellular compartment(inside the cells)that is hypetonic causing the cell to burst.

\section*{(2) DIFFUSION}
* This is the movement of solutes across a selectively permeable cell membrane from an area of higher concentration of solutes to an area of lower concentration of solutes until equilibrium is established . "Coasting downhill"--- diffusion is affected by:
(A) the size of the solutes:-. Larger solutes move less quickly and, consequently, have a lower rate of diffusion WHILST smaller solutes move more quickly and, consequently, have a higher rate of diffusion
(B) the concentration of the solutes :-solutes move from an area of higher concentration of solutes to an area of lower concentration of solutes
(C) the temperature of the solutes:- increases in temperature increase the rate of motion of solutes and, consequently, leads to a higher rate of diffusion WHILST decreases in temperature decrease the rate of motion of solutes and, consequently, leads to a lower rate of diffusion

\section*{(3) ACTIVE TRANSPORT}
* Movement of solutes across a selectively permeable cell membrane, usually against a pressure gradient and with the expenditure of metabolic energy(ATP), from an area of higher concentration of solutes to an area of lower concentration of solutes until equilibrium is established ."Pumping uphill" in active transport: a solute combines with a carrier on the outside surface of a cell membrane , the solute and carrier move to the inside surface of the cell membrane .Once on the inside surface of the cell membrane, the solute and carrier separate and the solute is released to the inside of the cell. Eg the sodium-potassium pump is an important active transport mechanism: Under normal conditions: sodium concentrations are higher in the ECF and potassium concentrations are higher in the ICF.So to maintain these conditions, the sodium-potassium pump continually pumps sodium out of the cells into the ECF and pumps potassium into the cells into the ICF .

\section*{(4)FILTRATION}
* Movement of solutes and solvent across a permeable cell membrane from an area of higher concentration of solutes to an area of lower concentration of solutes until equilibrium is established. This is influenced by two pressures ie colloid osmotic, (or oncotic pressure) and the hydrostatic pressure. Oncotic pressure is that pressure that prevents water from moving out from the intravascular to extravascular compartments to maintain vascular volume whilst hydrostatic pressure is that pressure that moves water outward from the intravascular to extravascular compartments

