\section*{INTRODUCTION}
-Metabolic processes of the body results with the production of large amounts of carbonic acids $\left(\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{CO}_{3}\right)$, sulfuric, phosphoric and other acids. These products of metabolism are transported to the excretory organs (lungs and kidney) via the ECF and the blood with minimal change in the plasma PH. This is accomplished by the combined functions of the buffer systems of the blood and the mechanisms of respiratory and renal systems.
- Clinical management of respiratory and metabolic disorders of patients undergoing surgical correction of cardiopulmonary disorders has been greatly improved by the development of instrumentations for rapid accurate measurement of oxygen and carbon dioxide in blood and expired air.
- The determination of blood gases and ph also plays an important role in the detection of acid/base imbalance and in following the effect of therapy.
- The measurement of blood gases, acid/base balance and ph of blood is very important in the management of patients in HDU(high dependency unit) and in ICU( INTENSIVE CARE UNIT). These are patients who can not breath normally especially those in a coma.
- The gases commonly measured are $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ and $\mathrm{CO}_{2}$. Although small amounts of these gases exist as dissolved gases in the blood , they are for the most part , chemically combined with other substances. $\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ exist chiefly as $\mathbf{H C O}_{3}{ }^{-}$while most of $\mathbf{O}_{2}$ is bound to haemoglobin to form oxyhaemoglobin. The PH of blood is dependent on the relative amounts of $\mathbf{H C O}_{3}{ }^{-}$and carbonic acid $\left(\mathbf{H C O}_{3}\right)$ which are present in the blood.

